":"1418","Lindsell, Essex, England":"Lindsell, Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1333–1 Jan 1412":"1333–1 januari 1412","1333–1412":"1333–1412","1345–Female":"1345–Overleden","1375–Male":"1375–Overleden","1379–1418":"1379–1418","1313–Male":"1313–Overleden","1315–Female":"1315–Overleden","1315":"1315","1379":"1379","1 Jan 1412":"1 januari 1412","1313":"1313","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1375":"1375","1418":"1418","Lindsell, Essex, England":"Lindsell, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1333–1 Jan 1412":"1333–1 January 1412","1333–1412":"1333–1412","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1379–1418":"1379–1418","1313–Male":"1313–Deceased","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","1315":"1315","1379":"1379","1 Jan 1412":"1 January 1412","1313":"1313","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1375":"1375","1418":"1418","Lindsell, Essex, England":"Lindsell, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Alger</i>. Pronounced with a soft <i>g</i> it is from Old French <i>Alg(i)er</i>, <i>Aug(i)er</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Adalgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gāri</i> ‘spear’); see   Auger  . Pronounced with a hard <i>g</i>, it is a variant of   Algar  .","Scottish and English: in Scotland, <i>Alger</i> may be a variant of   Algeo  .","German: from a shortened form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Adalgar</i> (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Aulgur","meanings":["English: variant of   Alger  ."]},{"name":"Auger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Gaston, Lucien, Marcel, Mederic, Normand, Raoul, Cecile, Emile, Fernand, Gaetan.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Auger</i>, which can be from ancient Germanic <i>Adalgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gaira-</i> ‘lance, spear’, or <i>Albgari</i>, with the first element <i>alb</i> ‘elf’. Compare   Auge  ,   Oge  ,   Ogea  , and   Osier  .","English: variant of   Alger  ."]},{"name":"Algar","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Algar</i>, representing the falling together of two Old English names, <i>Ælfgār</i> and <i>Æthelgār</i>, composed of the elements respectively <i>ælf</i> ‘elf’ or <i>æthel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gār</i> ‘spear’. It could also be from the much rarer Old English personal name <i>Ealdgār</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘old’ + ‘spear’. In East Anglia, it is more probably a variant of   Alger   (Old Norse <i>Álfgeirr</i>). See also   Agar  ,   Elgar  ."]},{"name":"Alker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Gerhart.","South German: variant of   Alger  .","English: habitational name from Altcar, Lancashire. This name means ‘marshland by the River Alt’, from Old Norse <i>kjarr</i> ‘marsh’ and the river name <i>Alt</i>."]},{"name":"Ager","meanings":["English (mainly Essex, Suffolk, and Northamptonshire): variant of   Alger   or possibly of   Edgar  .","Danish: habitational name from any of several places called Ager, meaning ‘plowed land’ (from a cognate of the English word <i>acre</i>).","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Adgari</i>, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>gari</i> (from <i>garwa</i>) ‘ready, eager’ or <i>gari</i> ‘spear’. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Alger was born in 1333, in Lindsell, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Alger, was 20 an